.TH HSH 1 "April 2026" "simple_shell" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
hsh \- simple UNIX command line interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
.RI [ filename ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX shell that reads and executes commands from standard input,
or from a file if one is provided as argument. It supports interactive and
non-interactive modes.
.PP
In interactive mode, a prompt
.B "$ "
is displayed before each command. In non-interactive mode (piped input or
file mode), no prompt is shown.
.SH COMMANDS
The shell searches for executable files in the directories listed in
.BR PATH .
If the command contains a slash, it is used as a direct path.
.PP
Commands can be separated using
.B ;
(sequential),
.B &&
(logical AND), or
.B ||
(logical OR).
.SH BUILTINS
.TP
.B exit \fR[\fIstatus\fR]
Exit the shell. If
.I status
is given, exit with that value.
.TP
.B env
Print the current environment.
.TP
.B setenv \fIVARIABLE VALUE\fR
Set or modify an environment variable.
.TP
.B unsetenv \fIVARIABLE\fR
Remove an environment variable.
.TP
.B cd \fR[\fIdirectory\fR]
Change the current directory. With no argument, change to
.BR $HOME .
With
.BR \- ,
change to the previous directory
.RB ( $OLDPWD ).
Updates
.B PWD
and
.BR OLDPWD .
.TP
.B alias \fR[\fIname\fR[=\fI'value'\fR] ...]
With no arguments, print all aliases. With names only, print those aliases.
With
.IR name = value
pairs, define or update aliases.
.TP
.B help \fR[\fIBUILTIN\fR]
Display help information for built-in commands.
.TP
.B history
Display the command history with line numbers.
.SH VARIABLES
.TP
.B $?
Expands to the exit status of the last command.
.TP
.B $$
Expands to the process ID of the shell.
.TP
.BI $ VARIABLE
Expands to the value of the environment variable.
.SH COMMENTS
A
.B #
character preceded by a space or at the start of a line begins a comment.
Everything after it is ignored.
.SH SIGNALS
The shell ignores
.BR SIGINT " (Ctrl+C)"
in interactive mode. Child processes receive the default signal handling.
.SH EXIT STATUS
The shell returns the exit status of the last command executed, or 127
if a command is not found.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B ~/.simple_shell_history
History file loaded at startup and saved on exit.
.SH EXAMPLES
Interactive mode:
.PP
.nf
$ ./hsh
$ ls -l /tmp
$ echo $?
0
$ exit
.fi
.PP
Non-interactive mode:
.PP
.nf
$ echo "ls -la" | ./hsh
$ echo "ls /var && echo ok" | ./hsh
.fi
.PP
File mode:
.PP
.nf
$ ./hsh commands.txt
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR sh (1),
.BR dash (1),
.BR bash (1),
.BR fork (2),
.BR execve (2),
.BR waitpid (2)
